<subSubSection id="C331B6BF2A3444438ACFFF2F2A13FD0A" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B94E5342A3444438ACFFF2F2B7CFEBE" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis id="B95F39262A3444438ACFFF2F2E6DFF12" bold="true" box="[199,315,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Remarks.</emphasis>
The four species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2B9EB72A34444388B3FF2F2C12FF12" authorityName="Norman" authorityYear="1903" box="[699,836,151,177]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Doryporellidae" genus="Doryporella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95F39262A34444388B3FF2F2C12FF12" box="[699,836,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Doryporella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been thoroughly described and illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBA98C52A3444438A9FFF032EF5FF76" author="Grischenko, A. V. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D." box="[151,419,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" pagination="247 - 264" refId="ref13343" refString="Grischenko, A. V., Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D. (2000) Systematics and phylogeny of the cheilostome bryozoan Doryporella. Zoologica Scripta, 29, 247 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1463 - 6409.2000.00038. x" type="journal article" year="2000">
Grischenko 
<emphasis id="B95F39262A3444438B17FF032E0EFF76" box="[287,344,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
(2000
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBA98C52A3444438BA6FF032EBDFF76" author="Grischenko, A. V. &amp; Taylor, P. D. &amp; Mawatari, S. F." box="[430,491,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" pagination="327 - 332" refId="ref13400" refString="Grischenko, A. V., Taylor, P. D. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. (2004) Doryporella smirnovi sp. nov. (Bryozoa: Cheilostomata) and its impact on phylogeny and classification. Zoological Science, 21, 327 - 332. https: // doi. org / 10.2108 / zsj. 21.327" type="journal article" year="2004">2004</bibRefCitation>
). No 
<typeStatus id="54905B962A344443882FFF032D01FF76" box="[551,599,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2B9EB72A34444388E8FF032C2EFF76" box="[736,888,187,213]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Doryporellidae" genus="Doryporella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="spathulata">
<emphasis id="B95F39262A34444388E8FF032C2EFF76" box="[736,888,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">D. spathulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<typeStatus id="54905B962A34444389B8FF032CB6FF76" box="[944,992,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus, was illustrated by these authors, although among the specimens examined (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBA98C52A3444438907FF672B46FF5A" author="Grischenko, A. V. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D." box="[783,1040,223,249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" pagination="247 - 264" refId="ref13343" refString="Grischenko, A. V., Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D. (2000) Systematics and phylogeny of the cheilostome bryozoan Doryporella. Zoologica Scripta, 29, 247 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1463 - 6409.2000.00038. x" type="journal article" year="2000">
Grischenko 
<emphasis id="B95F39262A3444438990FF672C99FF5A" box="[920,975,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
, p. 248) some are from the Swedish Arctic Expedition and collected off 
<collectingCountry id="F33CA5A42A3444438821FEBB2DD9FEBE" box="[553,655,259,285]" name="Svalbard and Jan Mayen" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Svalbard</collectingCountry>
, as the 
<typeStatus id="54905B962A34444388EAFEBB2C44FEBE" box="[738,786,259,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">type</typeStatus>
material illustrated here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94E5342A3444438ACFFE9F2A2CFEC6" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">
The 
<specimenCount id="9D2D2EBD2A3444438AF3FE9F2ED2FEE2" box="[251,388,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" type="generic" typeStatus="syntype">two syntype</specimenCount>
colonies are both fan-shaped, 3.8 x 
<quantity id="4CD348D12A344443892BFE9E2C2CFEE2" box="[803,890,294,321]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus id="54905B962A3444438981FE9F2CA5FEE1" box="[905,1011,295,322]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">lectotype</typeStatus>
) and 3.5 x 
<quantity id="4CD348D12A3444438E7EFE9F2B9BFEE2" box="[1142,1229,295,321]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus id="54905B962A3444438ED4FE9F2A21FEE1" box="[1244,1399,295,322]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">paralectotype</typeStatus>
) in size respectively, with subsequent generations of autozooids budded only distally from the ancestrula (
<figureCitation id="1310F9B12A3444438F1BFEF32A3AFEC6" box="[1299,1388,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-110@2.[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Doryporella spathulifera (Smitt, 1868), Lectotype (designated here) SMNH-Type-1729a, Hinlopen Strait, Svalbard, Norway. A. General view of the fan-shaped colony with subsequent generations of zooids budded only distally from the ancestrula. B. Close-up of the tatiform ancestrula and periancestrular zooids. C. View of colony growing edge showing paired distal pore chamber windows. Asterisks indicate kenozooidal ovicells. D. Group of ovicellate zooids showing ovicells produced either by a kenozooid (asterisks) or the distal autozooid, the suboral spatula-like spine and triangular avicularia mandibles. Scale bars: A = 2 mm; B–D = 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6424504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6424504/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94E5342A3444438ACFFED72ACEFDC2" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">
The study of this material allows a better observation of the ancestrula confirming it to be tatiform (
<figureCitation id="1310F9B12A3444438F3EFED72ADBFE2A" box="[1334,1421,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-110@2.[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Doryporella spathulifera (Smitt, 1868), Lectotype (designated here) SMNH-Type-1729a, Hinlopen Strait, Svalbard, Norway. A. General view of the fan-shaped colony with subsequent generations of zooids budded only distally from the ancestrula. B. Close-up of the tatiform ancestrula and periancestrular zooids. C. View of colony growing edge showing paired distal pore chamber windows. Asterisks indicate kenozooidal ovicells. D. Group of ovicellate zooids showing ovicells produced either by a kenozooid (asterisks) or the distal autozooid, the suboral spatula-like spine and triangular avicularia mandibles. Scale bars: A = 2 mm; B–D = 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6424504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6424504/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
), about 290 µm long by 220 µm wide; nine spines, about 70 µm long, are placed on the smooth gymnocyst and encircle the subcircular opesia, 175 µm long by 165 µm wide; the gymnocyst is well-developed proximally (90–100 µm); the opesia is outlined by a raised rim indented by the spines. An additional observation is related to the ovicell, which in the same colony can either be kenozooidal, occupying the space between autozooids and developed at the colony growing edge (
<figureCitation id="1310F9B12A3444438B9FFD9B2EA6FD9E" box="[407,496,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-110@2.[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Doryporella spathulifera (Smitt, 1868), Lectotype (designated here) SMNH-Type-1729a, Hinlopen Strait, Svalbard, Norway. A. General view of the fan-shaped colony with subsequent generations of zooids budded only distally from the ancestrula. B. Close-up of the tatiform ancestrula and periancestrular zooids. C. View of colony growing edge showing paired distal pore chamber windows. Asterisks indicate kenozooidal ovicells. D. Group of ovicellate zooids showing ovicells produced either by a kenozooid (asterisks) or the distal autozooid, the suboral spatula-like spine and triangular avicularia mandibles. Scale bars: A = 2 mm; B–D = 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6424504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6424504/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
), or produced by the distal zooid and occupying most of its frontal surface. In this latter case, the distal zooid sometimes fails to bud the frontal, centrally placed, adventitious avicularium (
<figureCitation id="1310F9B12A3444438F3BFDFF2ADCFDC2" box="[1331,1418,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-110@2.[159,1428,754,1722]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Doryporella spathulifera (Smitt, 1868), Lectotype (designated here) SMNH-Type-1729a, Hinlopen Strait, Svalbard, Norway. A. General view of the fan-shaped colony with subsequent generations of zooids budded only distally from the ancestrula. B. Close-up of the tatiform ancestrula and periancestrular zooids. C. View of colony growing edge showing paired distal pore chamber windows. Asterisks indicate kenozooidal ovicells. D. Group of ovicellate zooids showing ovicells produced either by a kenozooid (asterisks) or the distal autozooid, the suboral spatula-like spine and triangular avicularia mandibles. Scale bars: A = 2 mm; B–D = 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6424504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6424504/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94E5342A3444438ACFFDD32A13FD0A" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">
Compared to size measurements reported in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBA98C52A34444388B2FDD32C98FD26" author="Grischenko, A. V. &amp; Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D." box="[698,974,619,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" pagination="247 - 264" refId="ref13343" refString="Grischenko, A. V., Mawatari, S. F. &amp; Taylor, P. D. (2000) Systematics and phylogeny of the cheilostome bryozoan Doryporella. Zoologica Scripta, 29, 247 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1463 - 6409.2000.00038. x" type="journal article" year="2000">
Grischenko 
<emphasis id="B95F39262A344443894AFDD32C2CFD26" box="[834,890,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
(2000)
</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<typeStatus id="54905B962A3444438E0AFDD32B0FFD26" box="[1026,1113,619,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">syntype</typeStatus>
colony shows slightly larger autozooids and ovicells, but narrower opesia (
<tableCitation id="C6A9D08F2A3444438891FD372DBAFD0A" box="[665,748,655,681]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,728,752]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Measurements in µm of Doryporella spathulifera (Smitt, 1868), Svalbard, Norway; SMNH-Type-1729a." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF54B5BC2A3444438A9FFD602A39FD52" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" tableUuid="DF54B5BC2A3444438A9FFD602A39FD52">Table 1</tableCitation>
); frontal and latero-oral avicularia are similar in size.
</paragraph>
